    <naif_host_id>VL2</naif_host_id>
    <description>The Viking Landers were the first successful spacecraft to operate on the surface of Mars from 1976 to April 1980, with Viking Lander 1 continuing until November 1982. In 1981, Viking Lander 1 was renamed to honor Tim Mutch, who led the Lander Imaging Team and tragically passed away in a climbing accident. The two identical landers housed various instruments within a hexagonal prism structure supported above the surface by three legs. Key components included cameras, scientific instruments for atmospheric and geological studies, and communication antennas. The landers weighed about 610 kg and generated power using radioisotope thermoelectric generators (RTGs). The scientific investigations consisted of eight experiments, including atmospheric measurements, seismic activity, soil composition analysis, and biological experiments aimed at detecting life. The landers provided significant insight into Mars's environment and soil properties, making them pivotal in planetary exploration.</description>
